<HEADLINE>
<P>
SEE HOW HE RUNS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Your puff piece on John Garamendi ("The Loner," by Bill Stall, April 24) 
missed two minuses (and, to be fair, one plus). 
</P>
<P>
 Two of Garamendi's principal achievements were to increase the state 
Department of Insurance budget and to drive a number of insurance companies out 
of California. 
</P>
<P>
 On the plus side, Garamendi has come out in favor of the no-fault concept, 
which, because of pervasive fraud, is the only system that will ever bring auto 
insurance rates down. 
</P>
<P>
 WILLIAM H. SUTER 
</P>
<P>
 South Pasadena 
</P>
<P>
 A photograph accompanying the Garamendi article showed the commissioner 
picking artichokes. How many did he actually pick -- ouch! -- without gloves? 
Judging from the expression on his face, at the time the picture was taken, he 
may have already picked one or two -- ouch! Those prickly thistles can draw 
blood. 
</P>
<P>
 The photographer is to be commended for an excellent example of truth in 
advertising. 
</P>
<P>
 MARCELLA MEHARG 
</P>
<P>
 Los Angeles 
</P>
<P>
 The most distinctive aspect of this Berkeley-educated bureaucrat's career 
stems from a job title that could have come out of the pages of "Atlas 
Shrugged": state insurance commissioner. Emboldened by the socialist bromides 
of John F. Ken- nedy's New Frontier, Garamendi and his bunch have launched an 
assault on every individual right from a medical livelihood to ownership of 
property. 
</P>
<P>
 Like his comrade, Rhodes scholar Bill Clinton, Garamendi is the 
personification of the follower. He has accepted every statist notion he's been 
offered. His ideas are not new; his principles are the dying gasps of 
socialism. 
</P>
<P>
 SCOTT HOLLERAN 
</P>
<P>
 Glendale 
</P>
<P>
 I'm not certain that Garamendi represents the best interests of the citizens 
of California. Nor am I convinced that he would be an honest governor or an 
effective one. But he does, however, represent a new type of politician: one 
who uses the public interest for his own purposes under the guise of serving 
it. 
</P>
<P>
 MARC H. WEISS 
</P>
<P>
 Woodland Hills 
</P>
<P>
 Garamendi does have a "beautiful family," but on a planet that's reeling from 
the effects of overpopulation, isn't it incumbent on our public officials to 
set a better example -- two children, for example, instead of six? That 
supposedly well-educated couples consider it perfectly OK to have six children 
astounds me. 
</P>
<P>
 BETTY JEAN BRITE 
</P>
<P>
 Santa Monica 
</P>
<P>
 In my opinion, and with all due respect, I think John Garamendi is pure hokum. 
</P>
<P>
