<HEADLINE>
<P>
FIRST IMPRESSIONS: 20,000 LEEKS UNDER THE SEA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By S. IRENE VIRBILA 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A celluloid-bright yellow submarine of exaggerated cartoon dimensions is now 
docked at the foot of the Century City Shopping Center. Topped, improbably, 
with an olive on a toothpick, the new sandwich palace Dive! launches Steven 
Spielberg as restaurateur (with a little help from Chicago-based Levy 
Restaurants, which developed and runs the place). Last weekend kids, parents 
and assorted caretakers in tow, lined up by the hundreds. It was an unruly lot, 
but one willing to wait the wait to be among the first to climb aboard the 
beckoning ship. 
</P>
<P>
 "Cool," my 10-year-old escort pronounced the decor awash in dials and 
trappings of the deep. Not so cool, when we were told we had yet another hour 
to wait in the bar. "Keep your eye on this coaster; it lights up when your 
table is ready," the crewman told me. The room dimmed. Sirens blared, lights 
flashed as the submarine restaurant prepared to dive. How did I know this? 
D.I.V.E. flashed on the 210-foot screen and we seemed to sink through a flurry 
of bubbles many fathoms below. Enthralled by the eerie blue underwater voyage, 
we munched on fries (very good) with two of nine sauces until our coaster 
(finally) lit up. Later, the sub prepared to dive again (and again) as we 
waited for our order of USS Humongous. 
</P>
<P>
 That's a submarine sandwich sampler for four ($13.95 per diver). The theme -- 
if you hadn't guessed -- is the "reinvented submarine sandwich served up in 18 
fashions, from traditional cold cuts and Italian meatballs to brick 
oven-roasted steak, even fajitas and Chinese chicken salad, plus three 
vegetarian versions. There's a good, if overdressed, chopped vegetable salad. 
And for dessert, a warm cookie sundae topped with white chocolate ice cream and 
a billowing cloud of whipped cream. Too sweet?, I asked the kids. No! But next 
time, they insisted, they're having the burger. 
</P>
<P>
 * Dive!, Century City Shopping Center & Marketplace, 10250 Santa Monica Blvd., 
West Los Angeles. (310) 788-DIVE. Open daily for lunch and dinner. Valet 
parking. All major credit cards accepted. Full bar. Subs $7.95-$12.95; kids' 
subs $4.95.  
</P>
<P>
 S. IRENE VIRBILA 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Restaurant Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA052294-0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 044057 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
May 22, 1994, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Calendar; Page 83; Calendar Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
334 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
OLNEY'S MANTLE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Regarding "Leading L.A. to the Light," by Sean Mitchell (May 8): 
</P>
<P>
 Mitchell's story gives the impression that via "Which Way, L.A.?" Warren Olney 
has become the voice of Los Angeles public radio: "In the continuing social 
disarray that is Los Angeles, it has sometimes seemed that if anyone is pulling 
the city together . . . it's, of all people, Warren Olney." 
</P>
<P>
 I disagree. My candidate for the voice of Los Angeles public radio is 
KPCC-FM's Larry Mantle. Mantle is doing on his nightly "Airtalk" show exactly 
what Olney is doing, and has been doing it for more than nine years with the 
personality, sense of humor and enthusiasm Olney lacks. Olney's deadpan 
approach bores me. 
</P>
<P>
 Mantle has many of the same guests, usually in studio (why is it a matter of 
pride to Olney that he has no in-studio guests?), and he is just as 
well-informed and articulate. Both men have a following at their respective 
stations. And yet, it is Olney who is given a write-up, while Mantle is ignored 
and avoided by every newspaper and magazine in Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
 MICHAEL LIGHTCAP 
</P>
<P>
 Los Angeles 
</P>
<P>
 Mitchell's profile attracted me and pleased me by summarizing Olney's 
professional resume, his personal relationships, his diligence and public 
spirit as revealed in his radio program. Good thing the folks at KCRW-FM want 
him to continue the daily discussions. 
</P>
<P>
 The profile, unfortunately, also revealed at least one of Olney's 
shortcomings: Having enjoyed Olney's evenhanded questioning of radio guests for 
the last two years, I was surprised to see Mitchell quote him twice using the 
name of the Lord Jesus casually. 
</P>
<P>
 All of Olney's sensitivity to people of different ethnicities needs to extend 
to people's religious beliefs. Those who respect Christians' beliefs avoid such 
casual references to the Godhead, just as they avoid ethnic slurs out of 
respect for ethnically diverse people. Let's not reduce multiculturalism to 
matters of ethnicity, gender bias and sexual orientation only. 
</P>
<P>
 PATRICIA L. GEDDES 
</P>
<P>
 Artesia 
</P>
</TEXT>
