<HEADLINE>
<P>
COUNTYWIDE FOCUS: OAK PARK; SEASON'S 1ST BRUSH FIRE BURNS 3-ACRE FIELD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SCOTT HADLY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A grass fire in Oak Park on Saturday afternoon was the first brush fire of the 
season, a Ventura County Fire Department spokeswoman said. 
</P>
<P>
 The blaze burned a three-acre field next to a residential area on the 6500 
block of Oak Springs Drive about 4 p.m., the spokeswoman said. The cause of the 
blaze is still under investigation.  
</P>
<P>
 It took firefighters -- using seven engines, a water tender and a bulldozer -- 
a little over an hour to extinguish the blaze, she said. SCOTT HADLY 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA052294-0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 044179 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
May 22, 1994, Sunday, Ventura West Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part B; Page 3; Column 1 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
217 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
COUNTYWIDE FOCUS: OJAI; 2 YOUTHS CHARGED WITH RACIAL ASSAULT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By TRACY WILSON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Two Ojai teen-agers have been charged with misdemeanor assault for the April 8 
beating of a 14-year-old boy near Matilija Junior High School, prosecutors 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 The youths, both 17, face up to six months in jail for the alleged battery, 
which law-enforcement officials have described as racially motivated. 
</P>
<P>
 The boy, a white Matilija student, was walking home from school when seven 
Latino youths yelled threats from their car, Sheriff's Cmdr. Joe Harwell said. 
</P>
<P>
 "They told the kid, 'You better run,' " Harwell said. When the boy didn't run, 
the youths allegedly jumped from the car and punched and kicked him. Witnesses 
said one assailant yelled "Brown power!" before striking the boy, Harwell said. 
</P>
<P>
 None of the youths knew the victim, who was treated for minor injuries, 
Harwell said. 
</P>
<P>
 "This boy was knocked to the ground and kicked in the head at least once," 
Harwell said. "There appears to be no motive other than the racial remarks that 
were made." 
</P>
<P>
 Four suspects, a 14-year-old Matilija student, two Nordhoff High School 
students ages 15 and 17, and a 17-year-old student at Chaparral continuation 
school, were questioned the next morning and released. 
</P>
<P>
 Two youths were charged with assault this week, Deputy Dist. Atty. John 
Cardoza said. Arraignment has not been set. TRACY WILSON 
</P>
</TEXT>
