<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING BRIEFING: THE IMPRESSIVE THING IS THAT HE SPUN AROUND ON EACH TOSS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MAL FLORENCE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Parry O'Brien, former world-record holder in the shotput and Olympic gold 
medalist in 1952 and 1956, showed that he wasn't past his prime while working 
for CBS radio at the Pan American Games in Puerto Rico in 1979. When he 
returned to his hotel room one night, two men tried to rob him. He threw one 
down a staircase and the other over a balcony into a garden area. "You might 
say I set a record for thug tossing," O'Brien said. 
</P>
<P>
 Trivia time: What is the longest golf hole in the world?  
</P>
<P>
 Swampland: Outfielder Andy Van Slyke of the Pittsburgh Pirates, after hearing 
that Len Dykstra of the Phillies had quit using chewing tobacco, then learning 
otherwise at Veterans Stadium: "I thought I was going to get foot cancer," he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 Murderers' row: Angel pitcher Joe Magrane at the Orange County Sports Assn. 
luncheon, when asked what American League hitters he has the most difficulty 
with: "Right now, I would have to say one through nine." 
</P>
<P>
 FYI: Six prominent athletes attended Galileo High in the North Beach area of 
San Francisco: O.J. Simpson, football; Joe DiMaggio, baseball; Hank Luisetti, 
basketball; Grover Klemmer, track and field; Fred Apostoli, boxing, and Lawson 
Little, golf. Klemmer is a former world record holder in the 400 meters; 
Apostoli was middleweight champion in the late 1930s, and Little won the U.S. 
Open in 1940.  
</P>
<P>
 Keep talking: Craig MacTavish of the New York Rangers, on Finnish-born 
teammate Esa Tikkanen: "He's got to speak twice as much as everybody else 
because we can only understand 50% of what he says." 
</P>
<P>
 Last resort: Comedian Richard Lewis, on the last-minute calls sports 
broadcaster Marv Albert gets to be a guest on television talk shows: "Marv gets 
called, generally, when the guy from the Columbus zoo has to go to a peacock's 
funeral or something." Trivia answer: The 948-yard, par-seven at the Koolan 
Island Golf Course in Western Australia. 
</P>
<P>
 Quotebook: Former Dodger pitcher Jerry Reuss, on Candlestick Park: "This 
wouldn't be a bad place to play if it wasn't for the wind. I guess that's like 
saying hell wouldn't be a bad place if it wasn't for the heat." MAL FLORENCE 
</P>
</TEXT>
